<br>
The legalities of being married in the secular sense is a rather twisted puzzle to sort out. For one, it's a convenience in most states... it grants some (or all) powers of attorney, certain circumventions of probate on death of one member of the union, legal decisions on life and death matters, etc.<br>
<br>
The financial implications, wrong or right, extend to things such as insurance -- both in lower prices in the case of car insurance, and entitlement when it comes to company provided benefits -- credit approval, and such. <br>
<br>
As far as the 'married being taxed more heavily' it is true in some situations. The standard deductible for a married couple is less than that if both parties field separately. To the tune of about $1,800 or so. This does affect many, many people, but if your itemized deduction is greater than the the two filed-single income, that penalty disappears. I'm pulling numbers out of my hat because I'm too lazy at the moment to look them up (and the numbers I'm using will be way too high), but for easy math's sake, lets say that each person individually has a $5,000 deductible. Joint-filed has an $8,000 deductible. If your itemized deductions are less than $10,000, you suffer from 'the marriage penalty'. It is a bit more complex than that, because filing jointly will also, often, move someone into a higher tax bracket, but for simplicity's sake, what I've stated is a good portion of the marriage penalty.<br>
<br>
Owning a home (and paying a mortgage), or having a similar level of deductible will often eliminate the penalty. My wife and I experienced this whole anxiety this last year, and were fortunate enough with the house to avoid the 'marriage penalty'. It's an absolute killer on people who rent, though.<br>
<br>
A study done a while ago (again, too lazy to look it up, but it came across as very believable) pointed at the majority of homosexuals in long-term relationships were in a more affluent status than comparable heterosexuals in long-term relationships, so I'm going to go out on a limb and say that the 'marriage penalty' would not be as large an issue for that group. They're already homeowners, mid-upper to upper income brackets ... not all of them, but the averages were higher.<br>
<br>
There are also other advantages ... For a single person, if you've lived in your house for 2 years, you can sell it and keep up to $250,000 profit tax free. For a married couple, that increases to $500,000. (Of course if you both own individual homes, you still get the $500,000... but this is for a single home). <br>
<br>
Social security benefits also defer to a spouse, inheritance is in play as well, linked bank accounts available only to married couples provide lower surcharges and rates, etc. Some of these are now being extended to same-sex partners, but it's on a case-by-case, bank-by-bank, employer-by-employer change. <br>
<br>
I'd probably be too quick in assuming, but part of me wants to say that if only the union of a man and woman are validated as marriage, fewer institutions would be inclined to bend to public pressure to relax their marriage restrictions and provide them to same-sex couples.<br>
<br>
